1
00:01:40,860 --> 00:01:43,294
Looks deader
than a Paiute's grave.

2
00:02:16,529 --> 00:02:18,463
Well?

3
00:02:18,531 --> 00:02:20,465
That guy's awful slow
gettin' there.

4
00:02:20,533 --> 00:02:22,467
I feel sorry for him.

5
00:02:22,535 --> 00:02:25,231
Always in reach and never able
to do anything about it.

6
00:02:28,274 --> 00:02:30,367
I got a feeling
she could do better.

7
00:02:30,443 --> 00:02:33,378
You're boasting.

8
00:02:33,446 --> 00:02:35,573
- What'll you have? Whiskey?
- What've you got?

9
00:02:35,648 --> 00:02:38,811
- Whiskey.
- You ever see such a guy?

10
00:02:38,884 --> 00:02:42,980
All winter I've been thinking--
And all he's got is whiskey.

11
00:02:43,055 --> 00:02:45,148
- That's rotten, ain't it?
- Rotten.

12
00:02:46,158 --> 00:02:48,092
Two glasses
and a bottle.

13
00:02:53,499 --> 00:02:55,433
[ Clears Throat ]

14
00:03:10,850 --> 00:03:12,841
Well, what's on
you boys' mind?

15
00:03:12,918 --> 00:03:16,911
- Does somethin'
have to be on my mind?
- Well, there's mud in your eye.

16
00:03:32,438 --> 00:03:34,372
Friendly cuss, ain't he?

17
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:37,705
He's just getting around
to asking if his girl is still in town.

18
00:03:37,777 --> 00:03:40,871
His girl? If you mean
Rose Mapen, no.

19
00:03:40,946 --> 00:03:44,541
She went to Frisco
the first stage out this spring.

20
00:03:44,617 --> 00:03:47,450
That's a lie.
She said she'd wait.

21
00:03:47,520 --> 00:03:49,886
It's a fact.

22
00:03:53,626 --> 00:03:55,753
What a town.

23
00:03:55,828 --> 00:03:58,160
It's my guess
the married women run her out.

24
00:03:58,230 --> 00:04:00,960
Oh, no tar and feathers.
No rails.

25
00:04:01,033 --> 00:04:03,160
They just righteously
made her feel uncomfortable.

26
00:04:05,071 --> 00:04:07,005
Not that she ever
did anything, but--

27
00:04:07,073 --> 00:04:09,735
They just couldn't get over
being afraid she might.

28
00:04:12,678 --> 00:04:15,169
Say, what is there
to do in this town anyway?

29
00:04:15,247 --> 00:04:18,307
- Unless you wanna get in line
and woo Drew's daughter.
- We don't.

30
00:04:18,384 --> 00:04:22,514
The only other
unmarried woman I know
is 82, blind and a Paiute.

31
00:04:24,356 --> 00:04:26,290
That leaves you five choices.

32
00:04:26,358 --> 00:04:30,920
Eat, sleep, drink,
play poker or fight.

33
00:04:30,996 --> 00:04:32,930
Or you can shoot some pool.

34
00:04:32,998 --> 00:04:36,195
- I got a new table in the back room.
- That's just great.

35
00:04:45,444 --> 00:04:48,311
- I see Risley's still around.
- The sheriff?

36
00:04:48,380 --> 00:04:51,747
I thought he never
got closer than Reno
except on special calls.

37
00:04:51,817 --> 00:04:56,186
Hey, it wouldn't be
that rustling folks we're
talking about last fall?

38
00:04:57,923 --> 00:05:00,084
Could be.

39
00:05:02,027 --> 00:05:04,018
Gettin' to be a kinda
touchy subject, huh?

40
00:05:04,096 --> 00:05:07,395
They don't like
to talk about it except
with fellows they sleep with.

41
00:05:07,466 --> 00:05:10,458
- Afraid they'll find out
it's somebody they know?
- Maybe.

42
00:05:10,536 --> 00:05:13,061
- They lose some more this spring?
- Some.

43
00:05:13,139 --> 00:05:15,505
- How many?
- About 600 head.

44
00:05:15,574 --> 00:05:17,508
They got any leads?

45
00:05:17,576 --> 00:05:21,603
They picked up a small-herd
trail and signs of shod horses
down the south draw.

46
00:05:21,680 --> 00:05:24,114
Wouldn't everybody know
if there were strangers around?

47
00:05:24,183 --> 00:05:26,242
Sure.
And there hadn't been any.

48
00:05:26,318 --> 00:05:28,252
Except you two.

49
00:05:29,688 --> 00:05:32,316
- That ain't funny.
- [ Chuckles ]
Now who's touchy?

50
00:05:32,391 --> 00:05:34,791
You're talking about my business.
Stick to my pleasures.

51
00:05:34,860 --> 00:05:38,387
No offense, Carter.
I just wanted to let you know
where you two stand.

52
00:05:38,464 --> 00:05:40,432
- Listen--
- Take it easy, Gil.

53
00:05:40,499 --> 00:05:43,093
He's had five whiskeys,
and he's sore about Rose Mapen.

54
00:05:43,169 --> 00:05:46,263
- Keep your mouth shut
about Rose, see.
- Okay, Gil.

55
00:05:46,338 --> 00:05:49,068
I was just jokin'.
You can take a joke, can't you?

56
00:05:49,141 --> 00:05:51,268
Sure I can take a joke.
Some jokes.

57
00:05:51,343 --> 00:05:54,107
Lost any
over your way?

58
00:05:54,180 --> 00:05:56,978
No more than the winter
and the coyotes are to account for.

59
00:05:57,049 --> 00:05:59,574
You haven't got any ideas,
have you Farnley?

60
00:05:59,652 --> 00:06:01,779
Except not to have ideas.

61
00:06:03,155 --> 00:06:05,089
Make that clear.

62
00:06:07,092 --> 00:06:09,925
There are a lot of things
around here ain't clear.

63
00:06:16,001 --> 00:06:17,935
You still talkin'
about rustling?

64
00:06:18,003 --> 00:06:19,834
And strangers.

65
00:06:22,708 --> 00:06:25,871
<i>[ Man Whistles ]</i>
<i>Yippee!.</i>

66
00:06:32,351 --> 00:06:34,342
Looks happy, don't he?

67
00:06:34,420 --> 00:06:36,650
He just needed exercise.

68
00:06:36,722 --> 00:06:40,488
Whenever he gets low in spirits
or confused in his mind...

69
00:06:40,559 --> 00:06:43,221
he doesn't feel right
until he's had a fight.

70
00:06:44,363 --> 00:06:46,456
It doesn't matter
whether he wins or not.

71
00:06:46,532 --> 00:06:49,160
He feels fine again afterwards.

72
00:07:09,922 --> 00:07:12,618
Ain't that guy got there yet?

73
00:07:12,691 --> 00:07:14,625
[ Retching ]

74
00:07:23,902 --> 00:07:27,565
Holy cow! Now I'm gonna have
to start all over again.

75
00:07:34,313 --> 00:07:36,474
Somebody's sure in a hurry.

76
00:07:39,685 --> 00:07:43,485
- Did Darby use his fist?
- [ Chuckles ]
No, a bottle.

77
00:07:43,555 --> 00:07:46,854
- That's all right then.
- Hey, lay off Farnley, will ya?

78
00:07:46,925 --> 00:07:48,984
- Why should I?
- Because you hit him pretty hard.

79
00:07:49,061 --> 00:07:50,995
You made him look foolish.

80
00:07:51,063 --> 00:07:53,861
- Did I really get him?
- I thought you busted his neck.

81
00:07:53,932 --> 00:07:56,958
- No foolin'.
- [ Chuckles ]

82
00:07:57,036 --> 00:08:00,733
- Why, that no good--
- Shot right through
the head, I tell ya.

83
00:08:00,806 --> 00:08:03,240
- Where'd it happen?
- Down in the southeast corner
of the valley...

84
00:08:03,309 --> 00:08:05,470
- about eight miles from his ranch.
- You see him?

85
00:08:05,544 --> 00:08:08,570
No, sir, but Olsen did.
He found him laying
in a dry wash in the sun.

86
00:08:08,647 --> 00:08:10,808
<i>[ Man Continues ]</i>
<i>Shot right through the head.</i>

87
00:08:10,883 --> 00:08:12,817
- <i>[ Farnley ]</i>
<i>When?</i>
- <i>Well, about 2::00.</i>

88
00:08:12,885 --> 00:08:15,820
<i>He must've</i>
<i>been shot a lot earlier.</i>
<i>They picked his horse up...</i>

89
00:08:15,888 --> 00:08:18,152
- clear over near the ranch road.
- Any cattle missing?

90
00:08:18,223 --> 00:08:21,056
They couldn't tell.
There been so many working
that range down there.

91
00:08:21,126 --> 00:08:23,720
- Olsen send you for us?
- No, he's in such a hurry...

92
00:08:23,796 --> 00:08:27,095
he just yelled at me
to go get the sheriff.

93
00:08:27,166 --> 00:08:29,327
Hey,Jeff,Jeff--

94
00:08:37,543 --> 00:08:39,636
- Rustlers?
- Looks that way.

95
00:08:39,712 --> 00:08:41,976
- Who was it they got?
- Kinkaid.

96
00:08:42,047 --> 00:08:44,277
Kinkaid? Farnley's buddy?

97
00:08:44,350 --> 00:08:48,047
Yeah. They've been working together
ever since they were kids.

98
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:50,554
All the way from
the Panhandle toJackson's Hole.

99
00:08:50,622 --> 00:08:52,556
Sure, I knew him.

100
00:08:52,624 --> 00:08:56,993
Short, dark Irishman.
Didn't say very much.
Liked to sing a lot.

101
00:08:57,062 --> 00:09:01,123
These fellows will go
a long way to get the guy
that killed Larry Kinkaid.

102
00:09:03,502 --> 00:09:05,436
Lynchin'?

103
00:09:05,504 --> 00:09:07,438
I judge.

104
00:09:12,544 --> 00:09:16,173
- Got plenty of sand
but when he's mad, he's crazy!
- Wait, wait,Jeff. No rush.

105
00:09:16,248 --> 00:09:18,512
Even if they have got
a five-hour start.

106
00:09:18,584 --> 00:09:20,950
It's a good 500 miles
to the first border.

107
00:09:21,019 --> 00:09:23,010
Besides, there may
be a bunch of'em.

108
00:09:23,088 --> 00:09:25,648
It won't help Kinkaid now
to get yourself killed.

109
00:09:25,724 --> 00:09:28,215
That kid, Greene, got no
idea which way they went.

110
00:09:28,293 --> 00:09:30,284
Better wait till we
know what we're doing.

111
00:09:30,362 --> 00:09:32,296
We're all with you about Kinkaid.
You know that.

112
00:09:32,364 --> 00:09:35,060
Only, we ought to take our time
and form this posse right.

113
00:09:35,134 --> 00:09:38,262
So if we go, we're sure
to get what we go after.

114
00:09:39,271 --> 00:09:41,466
Okay. Make your posse.

115
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:44,100
Somebody better get
the sheriff first thing.
And Judge Tyler.

116
00:09:44,176 --> 00:09:47,009
Oh, what do we want with
old Tyler and his trials.

117
00:09:47,079 --> 00:09:50,480
Yeah, one good fast job
without no legal papers
and that's all there is.

118
00:09:50,549 --> 00:09:52,517
Remember, this ain't
just rustling. It's murder.

119
00:09:52,584 --> 00:09:55,075
Wait a minute, men.
Don't let's go off half-cocked...

120
00:09:55,154 --> 00:09:57,247
and do something
we'll be sorry for.

121
00:09:57,322 --> 00:10:00,985
We want to act in a reasoned
and legitimate manner.
Not like a lawless mob.

122
00:10:01,059 --> 00:10:03,926
Trouble with you, Davies,
you've been storekeepin' too long.

123
00:10:03,996 --> 00:10:06,089
You don't see
no profit in this.

124
00:10:06,165 --> 00:10:09,430
If any of you fellas had offered
to buy the rope from him--

125
00:10:09,501 --> 00:10:11,992
If we go, you're going
with us, fat gut.

126
00:10:13,405 --> 00:10:15,339
Brother, I wouldn't miss it.

127
00:10:15,407 --> 00:10:20,401
Only thing that'd bring me out
any faster would be <i>your</i> necktie party.

128
00:10:20,479 --> 00:10:22,504
Who knows,
maybe this <i>is</i> yours.

129
00:10:22,581 --> 00:10:25,709
I'll remember that
and see you handle the rope.

130
00:10:25,784 --> 00:10:29,242
In Texas where I come from,
we go and get a man
and string him up.

131
00:10:29,321 --> 00:10:31,949
That's right.
I say stretch 'em.

132
00:10:32,024 --> 00:10:35,118
It ain't just a rustler
we're after. It's a murderer.

133
00:10:35,194 --> 00:10:38,857
Larry Kinkaid, one of the finest,
most God-fearing men that ever lived...

134
00:10:38,931 --> 00:10:42,332
is lying out there right now
with a bullet hole in his head.

135
00:10:42,401 --> 00:10:45,598
If you let this go by,
there won't be nothing
safe around here.

136
00:10:45,671 --> 00:10:47,901
Our cattle, our homes.
Not even our womenfolks.

137
00:10:47,973 --> 00:10:51,306
I'm with ya, Farnley.
I'm going to get me
a gun and some rope.

138
00:10:51,376 --> 00:10:53,901
I'll be right back.
And if nobody else
will do it...

139
00:10:53,979 --> 00:10:55,913
me and you
will do it ourselves.

140
00:10:55,981 --> 00:10:57,972
Count me in too!

141
00:10:58,050 --> 00:11:00,644
Come on, boys.
Get your guns!

142
00:11:00,719 --> 00:11:03,950
Listen to me, men!
Don't lose your heads like this.

143
00:11:04,022 --> 00:11:07,048
You mustn't do this thing.
You must not!

144
00:11:07,125 --> 00:11:09,320
Shut up, Grandma.
Nobody expects you to go.

145
00:11:11,163 --> 00:11:14,428
Don't take it so hard, Mr. Davies.
You did all you could.

146
00:11:16,068 --> 00:11:18,832
- Will you do me a favor, Carter?
- That depends.

147
00:11:18,904 --> 00:11:21,634
I'm sending Joyce here
for the sheriff and Judge Tyler.

148
00:11:21,707 --> 00:11:23,868
I want you to go along
and help explain.

149
00:11:23,942 --> 00:11:27,378
You know how Art and I stand here.
We came in at a bad time.

150
00:11:27,446 --> 00:11:29,880
I've got to stay here
and see if I can't...

151
00:11:29,948 --> 00:11:32,109
stop 'em till they realize
what they're doing.

152
00:11:32,184 --> 00:11:35,449
If I can make this thing regular,
that's all I ask.

153
00:11:35,521 --> 00:11:38,081
- Come on. Let's go.
- Oh, wait a minute.

154
00:11:38,156 --> 00:11:40,454
- Do you know Mapes?
- The one they call Butch?

155
00:11:40,526 --> 00:11:43,927
Yes. The sheriff's made him deputy
for times he's out of town.

156
00:11:43,996 --> 00:11:47,488
And we don't want Mapes.

157
00:11:47,566 --> 00:11:51,969
<i>Well, they said I was</i>
<i>to be the executioner,</i>
<i>so I come all fixed.</i>

158
00:11:52,037 --> 00:11:54,597
Think I don't know
my business, huh?

159
00:11:54,673 --> 00:11:56,937
[ Gagging ]

160
00:11:59,611 --> 00:12:02,671
You don't look very well,
Mr. Davies.

161
00:12:02,748 --> 00:12:07,879
Maybe you'd better stay home
and rest up for the funeral.

162
00:12:07,953 --> 00:12:09,887
Maybe you could get the flowers.

163
00:12:09,955 --> 00:12:12,617
Boys wouldn't begrudge
a few flowers, even for a rustler.

164
00:12:12,691 --> 00:12:15,159
So long as he's a good dead one.
[ Laughing ]

165
00:12:32,077 --> 00:12:34,011
Get your hat and gun.

166
00:12:35,514 --> 00:12:37,573
I'm not going, Father.

167
00:12:37,649 --> 00:12:39,844
I don't wish any argument.
Do as I say.

168
00:12:39,918 --> 00:12:42,580
Perhaps this will do what
I've obviously failed to do--

169
00:12:42,654 --> 00:12:44,918
make a man of you.

170
00:12:57,436 --> 00:12:59,563
<i>[ Doorbell Rings ]</i>

171
00:13:01,306 --> 00:13:04,833
Scrape your boots,
put your hat on your hand
and straighten your wig.

172
00:13:06,545 --> 00:13:09,207
- Well?
- Why, is the judge at home, ma'am?

173
00:13:09,281 --> 00:13:11,215
- Yes.
- Can we see him?

174
00:13:11,283 --> 00:13:13,217
You got business?

175
00:13:13,285 --> 00:13:16,379
No, we just
dropped in for tea.

176
00:13:16,455 --> 00:13:18,446
Very funny.

177
00:13:18,523 --> 00:13:21,014
Mr. Davies sent us, ma'am.
It's awfully important.

178
00:13:21,093 --> 00:13:23,755
It's not
regular office hours.

179
00:13:37,442 --> 00:13:39,376
That the judge's
better half?

180
00:13:39,444 --> 00:13:42,106
His housekeeper.
His wife's dead.

181
00:13:42,180 --> 00:13:44,205
Well, you can see why
there's times when...

182
00:13:44,282 --> 00:13:47,251
the judge don't seem to be able
to make up his own mind.

183
00:13:47,319 --> 00:13:50,015
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Come in!. Come in!.</i>

184
00:13:50,088 --> 00:13:52,352
He says come in!

185
00:13:54,726 --> 00:13:58,025
Well, well, Carter,
how are things out
in your neck of the woods?

186
00:13:58,096 --> 00:14:00,564
- All right, I guess,Judge.
- You don't appear to have been...

187
00:14:00,632 --> 00:14:02,657
pining away, exactly,
since last I saw you.

188
00:14:02,734 --> 00:14:05,965
- And what can I do
for you gentlemen?
- We're here for Mr. Davies.

189
00:14:06,038 --> 00:14:09,439
Oh. How is my friend Davies?
Well, I trust.

190
00:14:09,508 --> 00:14:12,170
Yes, but could we see you alone
for a minute,Judge?

191
00:14:12,244 --> 00:14:15,736
- Oh, a matter of a private nature, eh?
- Yes, sir.

192
00:14:15,814 --> 00:14:18,339
<i>[ Art ]</i>
<i>Mr. Davies said particularly</i>
<i>just you and Sheriff Risley.</i>

193
00:14:18,417 --> 00:14:22,012
- Risley ain't here.
He deputized me.
- Where'd the sheriff go?

194
00:14:22,087 --> 00:14:24,487
Down to Kinkaid's ranch
early this morning.

195
00:14:24,556 --> 00:14:26,490
When will he be back?

196
00:14:26,558 --> 00:14:28,617
He didn't say.
Couple of days maybe.

197
00:14:28,694 --> 00:14:31,185
But anything you can tell him
you can tell me.

198
00:14:31,263 --> 00:14:34,027
Sure, we know that, Butch,
but we're here for Mr. Davies.

199
00:14:34,099 --> 00:14:36,397
If the judge thinks
it's your job, he'll tell you.

200
00:14:36,468 --> 00:14:38,402
Certainly, Mapes, certainly.

201
00:14:38,470 --> 00:14:41,598
All right. But if
it's a sheriff's job, call me, see.

202
00:14:41,673 --> 00:14:43,903
Naturally.

203
00:14:43,975 --> 00:14:46,705
Well, what can I do
for you gentlemen?

204
00:14:52,050 --> 00:14:54,985
<i>[ Horses Galloping ]</i>

205
00:14:55,053 --> 00:14:57,715
Ain't so much that Mr. Davies
don't want 'em to go.

206
00:14:57,789 --> 00:15:02,192
It's just he wants to make sure
a posse's sworn in to bring
him in for a fair trial.

207
00:15:02,260 --> 00:15:04,558
That's why we wanted
you and the sheriff to hurry.

208
00:15:04,629 --> 00:15:07,291
Confound it, men.
The sheriff's not here.
Today of all days.

209
00:15:07,365 --> 00:15:09,492
You can talk to them.
They'll listen to you.

210
00:15:09,568 --> 00:15:14,130
No. No, no, that's not my job.
I haven't any police authority.

211
00:15:14,206 --> 00:15:18,040
- Where are you going, Mapes?
- There's a posse forming,
in case you hadn't heard.

212
00:15:18,110 --> 00:15:20,044
That's sheriff work, ain't it?

213
00:15:20,112 --> 00:15:23,411
That's no posse. That's
a lawless, lynching mob.

214
00:15:23,482 --> 00:15:25,507
It'll be a posse
when I get there.

215
00:15:25,584 --> 00:15:27,552
I'm gonna deputize
them all proper.

216
00:15:27,619 --> 00:15:31,578
But you can't do that.
Risley's the only one
empowered to deputize.

217
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:37,323
<i>[ Sizzles ]</i>

218
00:15:39,264 --> 00:15:41,664
Should we tell Davies
you're coming,Judge?

219
00:15:41,733 --> 00:15:44,827
Yes. Yes, of course.
I suppose I'll have to.

220
00:15:44,903 --> 00:15:48,270
But doggone it, this is
the sheriff's job. Not mine.

221
00:15:55,247 --> 00:15:59,049
<i>[ Indistinct Whispering ]</i>

222
00:15:59,049 --> 00:16:00,482
<i>[ Indistinct Whispering ]</i>

223
00:16:05,189 --> 00:16:07,123
Coming along, Sparks?

224
00:16:09,026 --> 00:16:11,859
No, sir, Mr. Smith.
I don't guess so.

225
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:13,920
Oh, you better
come along, Sparks.

226
00:16:13,997 --> 00:16:18,024
Ain't every day we have a hanging
in a town as dead as this one.

227
00:16:19,303 --> 00:16:22,272
You won't have to do nothin'.

228
00:16:22,339 --> 00:16:24,671
All the real work's signed up.

229
00:16:28,545 --> 00:16:32,208
I just thought we ought
to have a reverend along...

230
00:16:32,282 --> 00:16:34,273
'cause there's gonna be
some prayin' done.

231
00:16:36,486 --> 00:16:39,353
Maybe you're right, Mr. Smith.

232
00:16:39,423 --> 00:16:43,291
Maybe somebody ought to go along
that feels the way I do.

233
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:45,419
<i>[ Smith ]</i>
<i>Davies'll loan you his Bible...</i>

234
00:16:45,495 --> 00:16:48,623
<i>so all the reading will be</i>
<i>done right at the burial.</i>

235
00:16:48,699 --> 00:16:52,294
Thank you, sir.
But I knows my text
without the book.

236
00:16:52,369 --> 00:16:54,633
They're kidding you, Sparks.

237
00:16:54,705 --> 00:16:58,766
I know, sir.
But maybe Mr. Smith's
accidently right.

238
00:16:58,842 --> 00:17:00,776
Maybe I ought to go along.

239
00:17:00,844 --> 00:17:03,005
There's an old horse
in my shed you can use.

240
00:17:03,080 --> 00:17:06,607
Thank you, sir.
I'll go and fetch it.

241
00:17:06,683 --> 00:17:09,652
Ya-haw!
Here comes Ma!

242
00:17:09,720 --> 00:17:11,881
- [ Cheering ]
- Come on! We're ready to go.

243
00:17:11,955 --> 00:17:14,446
Hiya, boys!

244
00:17:14,524 --> 00:17:16,458
[ Indistinct ]

245
00:17:16,526 --> 00:17:19,324
Whoa. Well, boys,
what are we waitin' for now?

246
00:17:19,396 --> 00:17:22,559
Judge Tyler.
Davies asked him to come over.

247
00:17:24,501 --> 00:17:26,867
[ Breathing Heavily ]

248
00:17:26,937 --> 00:17:29,030
I understand
how it is, men.

249
00:17:29,106 --> 00:17:34,237
My old friend Larry Kinkaid,
one of the finest and noblest--

250
00:17:34,311 --> 00:17:36,404
Cut the stumpin', Tyler.

251
00:17:36,480 --> 00:17:38,471
All we want
is your blessing.

252
00:17:38,548 --> 00:17:44,111
Of course you can't flinch from what
you believe to be your duty.

253
00:17:44,187 --> 00:17:48,021
But certainly,
you don't want to act hastily...

254
00:17:48,091 --> 00:17:52,721
in the same spirit of lawlessness
that begot this foul crime.

255
00:17:52,796 --> 00:17:54,787
Ah,Judge, before you get
ready to act...

256
00:17:54,865 --> 00:17:57,197
them rustlers will be
clear down over the Rio.

257
00:17:57,267 --> 00:18:01,169
One more word, Smith, and I'll
have you up for impeding
the course of justice.

258
00:18:01,238 --> 00:18:03,900
Judge, you can't impede
what don't move anyway.

259
00:18:03,974 --> 00:18:06,067
[ Laughing ]

260
00:18:06,143 --> 00:18:10,375
And you,Jenny Grier, a woman...

261
00:18:10,447 --> 00:18:12,506
to lend yourself to this.

262
00:18:12,582 --> 00:18:14,573
- Ha!
- [ Laughing ]

263
00:18:14,651 --> 00:18:17,279
Now, listen.
Listen, men.

264
00:18:17,354 --> 00:18:21,586
I've just found out
that Sheriff Risley's
already down at Kinkaid's.

265
00:18:21,658 --> 00:18:24,320
- That right,Judge?
- Yes. He's been there all morning.

266
00:18:24,394 --> 00:18:26,453
Yes. So you see,
probably everything's...

267
00:18:26,530 --> 00:18:29,294
being attended to
right now, legally.

268
00:18:29,366 --> 00:18:33,564
All you'll get out of it
is a long, hard ride.

269
00:18:33,637 --> 00:18:36,333
It'll be dark before long
and mighty cold.

270
00:18:36,406 --> 00:18:38,397
My advice is to come inside,
Have a drink...

271
00:18:38,475 --> 00:18:40,568
and let's wait till
we hear from the sheriff.

272
00:18:40,644 --> 00:18:44,375
Drinks on the house.
But only one round. I'm not
filling any bucket bellies.

273
00:18:44,448 --> 00:18:47,906
- I'll make it two.
- Any of you fellas wanna
stay in town, I can take six...

274
00:18:47,985 --> 00:18:50,078
<i>if you don't mind</i>
<i>sleeping doubles.</i>

275
00:18:50,153 --> 00:18:53,748
<i>[ Davies ] It's not like</i>
<i>you were giving up, boys.</i>
<i>It's just good sense.</i>

276
00:18:55,826 --> 00:18:57,760
<i>[Judge ]</i>
<i>Farnley, come back!.</i>

277
00:18:57,828 --> 00:18:59,921
I'm not asking you!
I'm telling you!

278
00:19:07,671 --> 00:19:11,801
You don't have to worry,Jeff.
This business is going
to be taken care of.

279
00:19:11,875 --> 00:19:16,642
Yeah, and I know who's
gonna take care of it. Me.

280
00:19:16,713 --> 00:19:21,980
I tell you now, whoever shot
Larry Kinkaid ain't coming
back here for you to...

281
00:19:22,052 --> 00:19:25,419
fuddle with your lawyers' tricks
for six months.

282
00:19:25,489 --> 00:19:28,720
Then be let off because Davies,
or some other whining old woman...

283
00:19:28,792 --> 00:19:32,228
claim he ain't bad at heart.

284
00:19:32,295 --> 00:19:36,197
Kinkaid didn't have
six months to decide
if he wanted to die.

285
00:19:36,266 --> 00:19:38,200
<i>Disbanding, men?</i>

286
00:19:38,268 --> 00:19:40,759
<i>[ Ma ]</i>
<i>Davies has just about</i>
<i>convinced us, Major Tetley.</i>

287
00:19:40,837 --> 00:19:43,203
- Of what, Mr. Davies?
- Why, of-- of--

288
00:19:43,273 --> 00:19:45,537
I take it you were acting
on the assumption...

289
00:19:45,609 --> 00:19:47,975
- the raiders left
for the south draw.
- Yes, of course.

290
00:19:48,045 --> 00:19:49,979
They didn't.

291
00:19:50,047 --> 00:19:52,538
- They went east by Bridger's Pass.
- That's through the mountains?

292
00:19:52,616 --> 00:19:55,141
<i>[ Tetley ]</i>
<i>Over the old stage road</i>
<i>to Pike's Hole.</i>

293
00:19:55,218 --> 00:19:57,652
- But that's 8,000 feet up.
- <i>[ Tetley ]</i>
<i>Approximately.</i>

294
00:19:57,721 --> 00:19:59,450
They'd be crazy
to go that way.

295
00:19:59,523 --> 00:20:03,323
Not so crazy perhaps,
Mr. Davies, knowing
how crazy it would look to us.

296
00:20:03,393 --> 00:20:05,486
How come
you're so sure, Tetley?

297
00:20:05,562 --> 00:20:08,326
Pancho saw them.
He was coming back from Pike's.

298
00:20:08,398 --> 00:20:12,664
- Had trouble getting
by them in the pass.
- <i>Si.</i> He not see me, I think.

299
00:20:12,736 --> 00:20:17,002
So, he was headed down the hollow
and I drive my horse out of the way.

300
00:20:17,074 --> 00:20:20,976
At first I think I say hello.
And then I think it's funny
how to drive the cattle then.

301
00:20:21,044 --> 00:20:23,171
- Cattle?
- Sure.

302
00:20:23,246 --> 00:20:25,976
- Why do you think I had
to get out of his road?
- Go on.

303
00:20:26,049 --> 00:20:29,348
When I see what mark
those cattle had,
I be very, very quiet.

304
00:20:29,419 --> 00:20:33,583
- <i>[ Mapes ] What kind of marks?</i>
- Oh, in the throat.
Three little whatchamacallem.

305
00:20:33,657 --> 00:20:35,921
That's Kinkaid's mark.

306
00:20:35,992 --> 00:20:38,552
- The dirty rats!
- [ Clamoring ]

307
00:20:40,430 --> 00:20:41,988
- How many were there?
- Forty head.

308
00:20:42,065 --> 00:20:43,327
- I mean rustlers.
- Three.

309
00:20:43,400 --> 00:20:46,267
Why were you so long
in bringing us this word, Major?

310
00:20:46,336 --> 00:20:51,797
I knew my son
would want to go along.
He was out on the range.

311
00:20:54,044 --> 00:20:56,444
Major Tetley,
you mustn't let this
be a lynching.

312
00:20:56,513 --> 00:20:58,447
It's scarcely
what I choose, Davies.

313
00:20:58,515 --> 00:21:01,712
Promise me
you'll bring them in
for a fair trial.

314
00:21:01,785 --> 00:21:04,117
I promise that I'll
abide by the majority will.

315
00:21:04,187 --> 00:21:07,452
Tetley, you know what's
legal in this case as well as I do.

316
00:21:07,524 --> 00:21:09,458
<i>[Judge ]</i>
<i>All we ask is a posse...</i>

317
00:21:09,526 --> 00:21:12,086
<i>to act under a properly constituted</i>
<i>offiicer of the law.</i>

318
00:21:12,162 --> 00:21:15,097
That's where I come in.
Risley made me a deputy.

319
00:21:15,165 --> 00:21:17,929
In that case, Mr. Mapes,
suppose you deputize the rest of us?

320
00:21:18,001 --> 00:21:21,027
That's not legal.
No deputy has the right to deputize.

321
00:21:21,104 --> 00:21:24,471
- How 'bout it, boys?
- Suits me, Butch.
Go ahead and pray.

322
00:21:24,541 --> 00:21:26,805
Mapes, you're
violating the law.

323
00:21:27,878 --> 00:21:29,812
Raise your right hands.

324
00:21:41,091 --> 00:21:44,686
I hereby solemnly swear that
I am duly sworn in as a deputy...

325
00:21:44,761 --> 00:21:47,059
in the case of the murder
of Larry Kinkaid.

326
00:21:47,130 --> 00:21:50,566
<i>And am willing to abide by</i>
<i>the decisions of the majority.</i>
<i>So help me God.</i>

327
00:21:50,634 --> 00:21:53,501
- Say ""I do.''
- [ All ]
I do.

328
00:21:57,774 --> 00:22:01,505
Tetley, you bring those men
in alive. Or as I'm justice
of this county...

329
00:22:01,578 --> 00:22:04,877
you'll pay for it
and every jack man
in your gang!

330
00:22:04,948 --> 00:22:07,815
- Tetley!
- You coming?

331
00:22:07,884 --> 00:22:10,375
Get my horse.
I'm going with them.

332
00:22:10,453 --> 00:22:13,422
Then get down to Kinkaid's.
Get the sheriff.

333
00:23:47,017 --> 00:23:49,884
We'll stop here
for a minute, gentlemen,
and breathe our horses.

334
00:23:49,953 --> 00:23:53,218
Winder, take one man with you,
go up to the top of that ridge...

335
00:23:53,290 --> 00:23:55,349
and see what you can see.

336
00:24:01,031 --> 00:24:03,226
Doin' this in the middle
of the night's crazy.

337
00:24:03,300 --> 00:24:05,427
I thought
you liked excitement.

338
00:24:05,502 --> 00:24:08,869
I got nothin' particular against
hangin' a murdering rustler.

339
00:24:08,938 --> 00:24:11,600
It's just, I don't
like doing it in the dark.

340
00:24:13,209 --> 00:24:15,507
There's always some crazy fool
to lose his head...

341
00:24:15,578 --> 00:24:18,069
- and start hangin' everybody in sight.
- Us?

342
00:24:18,148 --> 00:24:21,208
- Funnier things have happened.
- Well, we didn't have to come.

343
00:24:21,284 --> 00:24:23,775
It'd looked kind of funny
if we hadn't, wouldn't it?

344
00:24:23,853 --> 00:24:25,787
Besides, I like
to pick my own bosses.

345
00:24:25,855 --> 00:24:28,619
Whether we picked them
or not, we sure got 'em.

346
00:24:28,692 --> 00:24:34,221
That's what I don't like.
That Smith and Bartlett
shootin' off their mouths.

347
00:24:34,297 --> 00:24:37,824
Farnley...
and that renegade Tetley.

348
00:24:37,901 --> 00:24:40,995
Struttin' around his uniform
pretending he's so much.

349
00:24:41,071 --> 00:24:43,801
He never even saw the South
till after the war.

350
00:24:43,873 --> 00:24:48,537
Then only long enough
to marry that kid's mother
and get run out by her folks.

351
00:24:48,611 --> 00:24:51,444
Figured there was something
fishy about him dressing up like that.

352
00:24:51,514 --> 00:24:54,950
Sure. Why do you suppose
he'd be living in this
neck of the woods...

353
00:24:55,018 --> 00:24:57,009
if he didn't have
something to hide.

354
00:25:04,828 --> 00:25:08,594
Let's get out of here before
we all freeze to death.
Or else give it up.

355
00:25:08,665 --> 00:25:12,658
We'd be the laughingstock
of the country if we went home
on account of cold.

356
00:25:12,736 --> 00:25:14,670
<i>That's right.</i>
<i>But I'm telling you...</i>

357
00:25:14,738 --> 00:25:17,935
this rope's gonna
have to be thawed out
before it's fit to use.

358
00:25:18,007 --> 00:25:20,498
Mind if I come in
a little closer, Mr. Carter?

359
00:25:20,577 --> 00:25:24,308
No, come on. I'm finding it
kind of lonesome myself.

360
00:25:24,381 --> 00:25:27,817
-Powerful cold tonight, ain't it?
- I got a blanket if you want it.

361
00:25:27,884 --> 00:25:30,614
No. Thank you
just the same, Mr. Carter.

362
00:25:30,687 --> 00:25:33,383
But it takes all my hands
to stay on this old horse.

363
00:25:33,456 --> 00:25:36,152
- Better have
a couple of shots.
- I never use it.

364
00:25:37,927 --> 00:25:40,794
I sure wish we was well
out of this here business.

365
00:25:40,864 --> 00:25:43,662
Ah, it's a way
of spending time.

366
00:25:43,733 --> 00:25:47,464
It's man taking on himself
the vengeance of the Lord.

367
00:25:47,537 --> 00:25:49,801
[ Snickers ]

368
00:25:49,873 --> 00:25:52,933
You think the Lord cares
much about what's happening
up here tonight?

369
00:25:53,009 --> 00:25:55,170
<i>He marks the sparrow's fall.</i>

370
00:25:57,714 --> 00:26:00,945
I seen my own brother
lynched, Mr. Carter.

371
00:26:01,017 --> 00:26:03,485
I was nothin'
but a little fella.

372
00:26:03,553 --> 00:26:07,216
But sometimes now,
I wakes up dreamin' about it.

373
00:26:08,358 --> 00:26:11,156
Had he done what they...
picked him up for?

374
00:26:11,227 --> 00:26:14,719
I don't know. Nobody never
did know for sure.

375
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:20,091
[ Inhales, Exhales Slowly ]

376
00:26:20,170 --> 00:26:23,697
Well, a couple of shots more whiskey
can't do my soul any harm.

377
00:26:30,613 --> 00:26:33,013
Darby sure sells rotten liquor.

378
00:26:35,084 --> 00:26:38,144
Warms you up though.

379
00:26:38,221 --> 00:26:41,019
Feels like fire
creepin' in the short grass.

380
00:26:43,092 --> 00:26:45,583
I guess I'll just let her
spread a little while.

381
00:26:45,662 --> 00:26:49,257
<i>[ Farnley ]</i>
<i>Put out that light,you fool.</i>
<i>You wanna give us away?</i>

382
00:26:49,332 --> 00:26:51,823
Who to?

383
00:26:51,901 --> 00:26:53,926
Chuck that butt
or I'll plug you.

384
00:26:54,003 --> 00:26:57,495
Start something.
For every hole you make,
I'll make two.

385
00:27:05,682 --> 00:27:09,584
Looks like you're gonna have
a lot of shootin' to do, Mr. Farnley.

386
00:27:14,357 --> 00:27:16,655
Listen, something's coming!

387
00:27:20,129 --> 00:27:24,463
Whoa. Whoa.
Whoa.

388
00:27:26,870 --> 00:27:29,236
Hyah! Hyah, hyah, hyah!

389
00:27:38,515 --> 00:27:41,245
Fools! Stop him! Stop it!

390
00:27:48,591 --> 00:27:50,525
- What's the matter, Art?
- Shot.

391
00:27:50,593 --> 00:27:52,527
- Where?
- Left shoulder.

392
00:28:04,007 --> 00:28:06,498
You fool, you must be drunk.
Nobody but a drunken idiot...

393
00:28:06,576 --> 00:28:09,477
- would drive down a grade
in the dark like that.
- I thought it was a stickup.

394
00:28:09,546 --> 00:28:11,673
If those horses weren't
a sight smarter than you...

395
00:28:11,748 --> 00:28:15,115
that coach would be
at the bottom
of the canyon right now.

396
00:28:25,128 --> 00:28:27,062
<i>[ Ma ]</i>
<i>Rose Mapen!.</i>

397
00:28:31,701 --> 00:28:33,726
Hello, everybody.

398
00:28:35,772 --> 00:28:39,264
This is my husband,
Mr. Swanson of San Francisco.

399
00:28:39,342 --> 00:28:42,834
And, uh, my sister-in-law,
Miss Swanson.

400
00:28:42,912 --> 00:28:46,245
- Did you just get married, Rose?
-Just today.

401
00:28:46,316 --> 00:28:48,580
[ Laughs ]
No wonder you were
in such a hurry.

402
00:28:48,651 --> 00:28:50,585
<i>[ Ma Cackling ]</i>

403
00:28:50,653 --> 00:28:54,384
My name is Tetley, sir.
I can understand why
Miss Rose is in a hurry...

404
00:28:54,457 --> 00:28:57,449
to show the other ladies
what can be done
in the way of matrimony.

405
00:28:57,527 --> 00:29:01,156
- Thank you, sir.
- Say, what's everybody doing
up here this time of night?

406
00:29:01,230 --> 00:29:03,221
[ Clears Throat ]
Why, uh--

407
00:29:16,079 --> 00:29:18,013
Art's shot.

408
00:29:18,081 --> 00:29:21,050
[ Clamoring ]

409
00:29:26,856 --> 00:29:29,222
[ Chattering Continues ]

410
00:29:32,929 --> 00:29:35,591
- Gee, I'm sorry.
- <i>[ Art ]</i>
<i>You couldn't tell.</i>

411
00:29:35,665 --> 00:29:38,225
You hadn't ought to come
barging out like that.

412
00:29:38,301 --> 00:29:42,397
In the dark especially.
I couldn't tell who it was.
Everybody yelling like that.

413
00:29:42,472 --> 00:29:44,531
Aw, shut up!

414
00:29:51,514 --> 00:29:54,381
Here. I'm good
at this sort of thing.

415
00:29:54,450 --> 00:29:57,351
<i>[ Art ]</i>
<i>Look, do women</i>
<i>have to watch this?</i>

416
00:30:11,367 --> 00:30:13,631
<i>[ Art Screams ]</i>

417
00:30:18,875 --> 00:30:22,276
<i>[ Davies ]</i>
<i>There's room in the stagecoach</i>
<i>for you, Art.</i>

418
00:30:22,345 --> 00:30:26,247
Yeah, I better get you
on back to Darby's and get
some hot food into you.

419
00:30:26,315 --> 00:30:29,842
- <i>I'm all right.</i>
- Come on. Be a good boy.
Don't be stubborn.

420
00:30:29,919 --> 00:30:32,547
- Yeah, don't be a fool.
- Mind your own business!

421
00:30:38,895 --> 00:30:41,090
<i>Bring his horse over,</i>
<i>will ya?</i>

422
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:58,304
- She's his wife now and kind of new.
- Yeah, looks that way, don't it?

423
00:31:13,996 --> 00:31:16,362
I take it you've had
the privilege of knowing...

424
00:31:16,432 --> 00:31:19,833
- Miss Mapen before
she became my wife.
- That's right.

425
00:31:19,902 --> 00:31:24,305
And possibly you imagined
at the time there was some
understanding between you?

426
00:31:25,541 --> 00:31:28,066
Yeah, sure.

427
00:31:28,144 --> 00:31:31,010
- My wife is a very impulsive woman.
- That's what I'm saying.

428
00:31:31,144 --> 00:31:33,408
Needless to say,
I'm pleased to regard...

429
00:31:33,479 --> 00:31:36,346
any friend of my wife's
a friend of my own.

430
00:31:36,415 --> 00:31:40,078
However, I don't need to
remind you that the pleasure
of such an acquaintance...

431
00:31:40,153 --> 00:31:42,121
depends upon the recognition
by all parties...

432
00:31:42,188 --> 00:31:44,850
of the fact that
Miss Mapen is now my wife.

433
00:31:44,924 --> 00:31:46,858
She must be given
a little time...

434
00:31:46,926 --> 00:31:49,292
to become accustomed to her
new responsibilities.

435
00:31:49,362 --> 00:31:53,389
As yet, I must
confess that I'm jealous
of her least attention.

436
00:31:53,466 --> 00:31:55,400
You'll forgive me, I know.

437
00:31:55,468 --> 00:32:00,963
A bridegroom is prone
to be overly susceptible for a time.

438
00:32:01,040 --> 00:32:05,101
Later, when we've had time
to get accustomed
to our new relations...

439
00:32:05,178 --> 00:32:09,706
<i>I shall be delighted</i>
<i>to welcome you and others</i>
<i>of my wife's friends...</i>

440
00:32:09,782 --> 00:32:13,013
to our home
in San Francisco.

441
00:32:13,085 --> 00:32:15,747
If it is still her desire.

442
00:32:16,722 --> 00:32:18,656
Until then--

443
00:32:23,763 --> 00:32:26,630
Why, that superior little--

444
00:32:33,372 --> 00:32:37,069
Looks like Rose's took
onto herself a lot of trouble.

445
00:32:39,512 --> 00:32:41,537
Giddap! Giddap!

446
00:32:47,854 --> 00:32:49,947
<i>[ Gunshot In Distance ]</i>

447
00:32:50,022 --> 00:32:52,217
<i>[ Cattle Mooing ]</i>

448
00:33:13,012 --> 00:33:15,344
- Where are we?
- The Ox-Bow.

449
00:33:15,414 --> 00:33:17,939
There they are, gentlemen.

450
00:33:20,386 --> 00:33:24,789
I suggest we avoid any shooting
or rough work until they've had
a chance to tell it their way.

451
00:33:24,857 --> 00:33:26,882
Mr. Mapes and I
will do the talking.

452
00:33:26,959 --> 00:33:30,827
- The one that got Kinkaid
is mine. Don't forget that.
- He's yours when we're sure.

453
00:33:30,897 --> 00:33:33,798
<i>[ Tetley ]</i>
<i>Ten men will go with Mrs. Grier</i>
<i>and come up from behind.</i>

454
00:33:33,866 --> 00:33:38,064
<i>Bartlett, take six men</i>
<i>and work through those woods</i>
<i>in back of the cabin.</i>

455
00:33:38,137 --> 00:33:41,834
Gerald, you and Farnley
and the rest will go with me.

456
00:33:41,908 --> 00:33:43,842
Would you
like a gun, Mr. Davies?

457
00:33:43,910 --> 00:33:47,141
- No, thank you.
- Sparks?

458
00:33:47,213 --> 00:33:50,478
Thank you.
No, sir, Major Tetley.

459
00:33:50,549 --> 00:33:53,040
As you choose.

460
00:35:49,402 --> 00:35:52,701
- Get up!
- Drop it!

461
00:35:56,842 --> 00:35:59,003
Now put up your hands.

462
00:36:00,579 --> 00:36:02,513
<i>No sabe.</i>

463
00:36:02,581 --> 00:36:05,106
It's all right, brother.
You will.

464
00:36:20,166 --> 00:36:22,134
[ Yawning ]

465
00:36:23,402 --> 00:36:26,030
[ Groans ]

466
00:36:31,343 --> 00:36:34,574
Take it easy, mister.
Stay where you are
and put your hands up.

467
00:36:38,717 --> 00:36:41,151
Gerald,
collect their guns.

468
00:36:41,220 --> 00:36:45,384
- What do you want?
- Shut up! We'll tell you
when we want you to talk.

469
00:36:45,458 --> 00:36:49,019
This ain't no stickup, brother.
This is a posse if that
means anything to you.

470
00:36:49,095 --> 00:36:51,154
But we haven't done anything.

471
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:56,991
Gerald!

472
00:37:26,866 --> 00:37:28,857
Get 'em up!

473
00:37:59,165 --> 00:38:01,099
<i>[ Tetley ]</i>
<i>Tie them up!.</i>

474
00:38:01,167 --> 00:38:03,761
- Get in--
- All right, get in there.

475
00:38:06,872 --> 00:38:09,636
Well, at least
you might tell us what
we're being held for.

476
00:38:09,708 --> 00:38:12,302
- I'd rather you told us.
- <i>[ Horses Approaching ]</i>

477
00:38:29,828 --> 00:38:32,626
Well, we must be pretty important.
Or else awfully dangerous.

478
00:38:32,698 --> 00:38:34,632
It ain't that
you're so dangerous.

479
00:38:34,700 --> 00:38:38,158
It's just that most
of the men ain't never seen
a real triple hangin'.

480
00:38:38,237 --> 00:38:40,330
A hangin'?
What have we done?

481
00:38:42,841 --> 00:38:45,366
Aren't you even gonna tell us
what we're accused of?

482
00:38:45,444 --> 00:38:47,878
- Rustlin'. Ever hear of it?
- Rustlin'?

483
00:38:47,947 --> 00:38:50,575
And murder.

484
00:38:52,985 --> 00:38:54,953
Murder?

485
00:38:55,955 --> 00:39:00,085
Oh, Mr. Martin,
what did we do?

486
00:39:00,159 --> 00:39:02,184
It's all right, Dad.
There's some mistake.

487
00:39:08,179 --> 00:39:10,613
Remember me?

488
00:39:11,749 --> 00:39:14,684
- [ Grunts ]
- He's talkin' to ya, mister.

489
00:39:14,752 --> 00:39:17,186
- <i>No sabe.</i>
- He don't speak English.

490
00:39:17,255 --> 00:39:19,655
- I got a different notion.
- I'll make him talk.

491
00:39:19,724 --> 00:39:24,320
- <i>That'll do, Farnley!.</i>
- Listen, your wife had enough
of you playin' God Almighty.

492
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:27,489
Who picked you
for this job anyhow?

493
00:39:27,565 --> 00:39:30,227
We got him. I say
let's swing him before
we all freeze to death!

494
00:39:30,301 --> 00:39:32,394
You cold? Here's a fire.
Warm yourself.

495
00:39:32,470 --> 00:39:34,768
And I'll advise you
to control your tongue too.

496
00:39:34,839 --> 00:39:36,807
We'll get along better.

497
00:39:36,874 --> 00:39:39,536
- Who's boss of this outfit?
- I am.

498
00:39:39,677 --> 00:39:42,271
- And your name?
- Donald Martin.

499
00:39:42,347 --> 00:39:44,281
- Where you from?
- Pike's Hole.

500
00:39:44,349 --> 00:39:47,341
- <i>That's a lie!.</i>
- This gentleman's
from Pike's Hole.

501
00:39:47,418 --> 00:39:49,352
Would you like
to change your story?

502
00:39:49,420 --> 00:39:53,254
I just moved in three days ago.
I'm on Dave Baker's place
up on the north end.

503
00:39:53,324 --> 00:39:56,725
Dave Baker moved out
four years ago,
and the place is a wreck.

504
00:39:56,794 --> 00:40:00,286
The barns are all fallin' down
and the sagebrush is stickin' up
through the porch.

505
00:40:00,365 --> 00:40:03,596
Well, I bought the place
from him for $4,000
in Los Angeles last month.

506
00:40:03,668 --> 00:40:07,570
- [ Laughs ]
Then, mister, you was robbed.
- Well, that may be.

507
00:40:07,639 --> 00:40:11,598
But surely it's not so far
to Pike's Hole you can't go
over there and find out.

508
00:40:11,676 --> 00:40:13,871
My wife's there right now...

509
00:40:13,945 --> 00:40:19,349
- and my two kids.
- That's really too bad,
just too bad.

510
00:40:19,417 --> 00:40:22,318
Even in this godforsaken country,
I've got a right to a trial!

511
00:40:22,387 --> 00:40:25,220
You're getting a trial with 28
of the only kind of judges...

512
00:40:25,289 --> 00:40:29,020
murderers and rustlers
get in what you call
this ""godforsaken country.''

513
00:40:29,093 --> 00:40:31,823
So far, the jury
don't like your story.

514
00:40:31,896 --> 00:40:34,660
Well, I'm not
gonna say another word
without a proper hearing.

515
00:40:34,732 --> 00:40:37,997
<i>[ Ma ] Suit yourself.</i>
<i>But this is all the hearing</i>
<i>you're likely to get...</i>

516
00:40:38,069 --> 00:40:40,003
<i>short of the LastJudgment.</i>

517
00:40:40,071 --> 00:40:42,471
Have you any cattle
up here with you?

518
00:40:42,540 --> 00:40:46,806
<i>Hey, Mr. Martin?</i>

519
00:40:48,880 --> 00:40:51,348
[ Gagging ]

520
00:40:51,416 --> 00:40:53,816
[ Laughs ]

521
00:40:53,885 --> 00:40:56,718
I'm not gonna
ask you again.

522
00:41:00,058 --> 00:41:03,357
- Yes, I have.
- How many?

523
00:41:03,428 --> 00:41:05,794
- Fifty head.
- Where did you get 'em?

524
00:41:05,863 --> 00:41:08,525
From Mr. Kinkaid.

525
00:41:08,599 --> 00:41:10,897
That's just
what we figured, son.

526
00:41:10,968 --> 00:41:13,493
I'm no rustler though.
I didn't steal 'em!

527
00:41:13,571 --> 00:41:16,335
I bought 'em
and paid hard cash for them.

528
00:41:16,407 --> 00:41:18,739
My own cattle were so bad,
I didn't want to risk bringin' 'em up.

529
00:41:18,810 --> 00:41:22,541
So I sold them out at Salinas,
and I had to stock up again.

530
00:41:30,321 --> 00:41:33,449
Well, you can wait can't ya,
till you can see Kinkaid?

531
00:41:33,524 --> 00:41:36,152
- Or ask about me
over at Pike's Hole.
- That's a good one.

532
00:41:36,227 --> 00:41:38,787
He's wants us to wait
and ask Larry Kinkaid.

533
00:41:38,863 --> 00:41:41,127
<i>Gotta hand it to ya, Martin.</i>
<i>You're a cool one all right.</i>

534
00:41:41,199 --> 00:41:43,895
You know as well as we do,
Kinkaid can't tell us anything.

535
00:41:43,968 --> 00:41:47,096
- He's dead.
- Dead?

536
00:41:48,172 --> 00:41:50,504
<i>What do you think</i>
<i>we're up here for?</i>

537
00:41:50,575 --> 00:41:52,736
Well, how should I know?
He was all right yesterday afternoon.

538
00:41:52,810 --> 00:41:56,507
Listen. Why don't
you stop this farce
and take us in!

539
00:41:56,581 --> 00:41:59,550
'Cause the law's
slow and careless
around here sometimes.

540
00:41:59,617 --> 00:42:02,381
We're here to see
it's speeded up.

541
00:42:03,454 --> 00:42:05,513
- Who sent you up here?
- The sheriff.

542
00:42:05,590 --> 00:42:08,184
-<i>[ Gil ] That ain't true!.</i>
-<i>[ Smith ] Let's don't get</i>
<i>started again.</i>

543
00:42:08,259 --> 00:42:10,989
- <i>It's gettin'late.</i>
- The sheriff didn't
even know we were comin'.

544
00:42:11,062 --> 00:42:13,963
I beg your pardon.
I should have said
the deputy sheriff.

545
00:42:14,031 --> 00:42:17,762
Listen, men.
I'm not trying to obstruct justice...

546
00:42:17,835 --> 00:42:20,861
but just as this young man says,
this is a farce.

547
00:42:20,938 --> 00:42:23,634
And it'll be murder
if you carry it through.

548
00:42:23,708 --> 00:42:27,474
All he's asking is what
every man's entitled to--
a fair trial.

549
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:30,605
<i>You say you're innocent, Martin,</i>
<i>and I, for one, believe you.</i>

550
00:42:30,681 --> 00:42:32,808
<i>[ Ma ]</i>
<i>Then I guess you're</i>
<i>the only one, Arthur.</i>

551
00:42:32,884 --> 00:42:35,148
<i>If there's anyjustice</i>
<i>in your proceedings, Tetley...</i>

552
00:42:35,219 --> 00:42:37,153
it will only be
after a confession.

553
00:42:37,221 --> 00:42:39,485
And they haven't confessed.
They say they're innocent...

554
00:42:39,557 --> 00:42:41,718
- and you haven't proved they're not!
- Shut up!

555
00:42:41,793 --> 00:42:44,125
- <i>[ Punch Landing ]</i>
- Have you a bill of sale
for those cattle?

556
00:42:44,195 --> 00:42:47,892
Well, no, I haven't.
But Mr. Kinkaid said
it would be all right.

557
00:42:47,965 --> 00:42:50,991
I couldn't find him at the house.
He was out on the range!

558
00:42:51,068 --> 00:42:54,003
He didn't have
a bill of sale with him.
He said he'd mail it to me.

559
00:42:54,071 --> 00:42:56,699
Moore. How long you been
ridin' with Kinkaid?

560
00:42:56,774 --> 00:43:00,175
- Six years.
- Ever know him sell cattle
without a bill of sale?

561
00:43:00,244 --> 00:43:03,077
N-N-No.
Can't say that I ever did.

562
00:43:03,147 --> 00:43:06,981
[ Sniffles ]
Course, I can't remember
every head he sold in six years.

563
00:43:07,051 --> 00:43:10,214
- But it's customary for him
to give a bill of sale?
- Y-Yep.

564
00:43:10,288 --> 00:43:13,587
Ever know him to sell
cattle after spring roundup,
this or any other year?

565
00:43:13,658 --> 00:43:18,561
<i>I can answer that.</i>
<i>I heard him say myself</i>
<i>just a couple of days ago...</i>

566
00:43:18,629 --> 00:43:22,030
- he wouldn't sell a head
to nobody this spring.
- Well?

567
00:43:24,068 --> 00:43:27,765
I know it looks bad giving a dead man
for a witness, but it's the truth.

568
00:43:27,839 --> 00:43:31,297
- You don't believe me.
- Would you in my place?

569
00:43:31,375 --> 00:43:34,970
I'd do a lot of finding out,
before hanging men
who might be innocent.

570
00:43:35,046 --> 00:43:37,640
If it were only rustlin'
maybe, but-- but murder?

571
00:43:37,715 --> 00:43:39,649
No.

572
00:43:45,756 --> 00:43:48,953
<i>[ Ma ]</i>
<i>What are you tryin'to do,</i>
<i>play cat and mouse with 'em?</i>

573
00:43:49,026 --> 00:43:51,654
I would prefer
a confession, Martin.

574
00:43:51,729 --> 00:43:53,720
[ Sobs ]

575
00:43:57,068 --> 00:43:59,764
If you've got any doubts,
I say call off this party.

576
00:43:59,837 --> 00:44:01,998
Take 'em back toJudge
like Davies wants.

577
00:44:02,073 --> 00:44:04,701
This is only slightly any
of your business, my friend.
Remember that.

578
00:44:04,775 --> 00:44:07,471
Hangin's any man's business
that's around!

579
00:44:07,545 --> 00:44:10,207
If your stomach for justice
is coolin', Carter...

580
00:44:10,281 --> 00:44:13,546
I'd advise you to leave now
before we proceed any further.

581
00:44:13,618 --> 00:44:16,018
Otherwise,
your interruptions are gonna
become very tiresome.

582
00:44:16,087 --> 00:44:19,056
- I still don't like it!
Hangin' murderers is one thing,
- Take it easy.

583
00:44:19,123 --> 00:44:21,114
but to keep guys
you don't know for sure did it...

584
00:44:21,192 --> 00:44:23,126
standin' around sweatin'
while you shoot your mouth off...

585
00:44:23,194 --> 00:44:26,322
- that's another.
- Take it easy.
This ain't our picnic.

586
00:44:26,397 --> 00:44:29,662
If you keep on buttin' in,
I got a hunch it might be.

587
00:44:29,734 --> 00:44:31,929
You called
this old man, ""Dad.''
Is he your father?

588
00:44:32,003 --> 00:44:35,700
- No.
- Speak up, man.
You're taking it like a woman.

589
00:44:35,773 --> 00:44:39,539
Keep your chin up.
You can only die once, son.

590
00:44:39,610 --> 00:44:42,044
- No. He works for me.
- Uh-- U-Uh--

591
00:44:42,113 --> 00:44:45,378
- I didn't do it.
I ain't even got a gun.
- Then who did?

592
00:44:45,449 --> 00:44:47,781
Uh, uh--

593
00:44:50,121 --> 00:44:52,954
The Mexican did it.
He told me so.

594
00:44:53,024 --> 00:44:54,958
Eh, no--

595
00:44:55,026 --> 00:44:57,927
Uh,
I-I saw him do it.

596
00:44:57,995 --> 00:45:00,259
Juan couldn't have done anything.
I was with him all the time.

597
00:45:00,331 --> 00:45:02,265
Uh, yes, he did,
Mr. Martin.

598
00:45:02,333 --> 00:45:05,393
He was asleep,
and he didn't mean to tell me.

599
00:45:05,469 --> 00:45:08,199
But I was awake, and...

600
00:45:08,272 --> 00:45:11,639
I-I heard him
talkin' about it.

601
00:45:11,709 --> 00:45:14,735
The old man's feeble-minded.
He doesn't know what
he's talking about.

602
00:45:14,812 --> 00:45:17,178
He invents things.

603
00:45:17,248 --> 00:45:19,739
Well, if you've
got to go through
with this filthy comedy...

604
00:45:19,817 --> 00:45:22,911
-you can at least
let him alone, can't ya?
- Shut up!

605
00:45:22,987 --> 00:45:24,921
<i>Lay off,Mapes!.</i>

606
00:45:24,989 --> 00:45:28,254
First, he won't talk.
Now he talks too much.

607
00:45:30,928 --> 00:45:34,056
What's his name?

608
00:45:34,131 --> 00:45:36,065
Alva Hardwick.

609
00:45:36,133 --> 00:45:38,658
- And the other?
-Juan Martinez.

610
00:45:38,736 --> 00:45:41,500
<i>No, it ain't.</i>

611
00:45:41,572 --> 00:45:44,871
Still don't remember me, eh?

612
00:45:44,942 --> 00:45:46,933
I'm talkin' to you, mister.

613
00:45:48,279 --> 00:45:50,577
- <i>No sabe.</i>
- The devil you don't.

614
00:45:50,648 --> 00:45:54,243
Your name's Francisco Morez,
and the vigilantes would
like to get ahold of you.

615
00:45:54,318 --> 00:45:56,411
He was a gambler.
They want him for murder.

616
00:45:56,487 --> 00:45:59,354
- How about that?
- I don't know.

617
00:45:59,423 --> 00:46:01,755
<i>Stick together nice,</i>
<i>don't they?</i>

618
00:46:01,826 --> 00:46:04,659
Why do you keep asking me
all these questions? You don't
believe anything I tell you.

619
00:46:04,729 --> 00:46:07,562
There's truth in lies too,
if you can get enough of them.

620
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:10,623
What do you know
about the old man?

621
00:46:10,701 --> 00:46:13,169
I don't know,
he-- he was in the army.

622
00:46:13,237 --> 00:46:17,037
- Confederate or Union?
- I don't know. He's not
clear about it himself.

623
00:46:17,108 --> 00:46:19,702
Maybe both...
at different times.

624
00:46:19,777 --> 00:46:22,075
A half-wit
in the army?

625
00:46:27,451 --> 00:46:29,578
Attention!

626
00:46:32,156 --> 00:46:35,648
- Oh, he's forgotten.
- Not that.

627
00:46:35,726 --> 00:46:38,160
I'll make a deal
with you, Martin.

628
00:46:38,229 --> 00:46:41,892
Tell us which of you shot Kinkaid,
and the other two can wait.

629
00:46:44,201 --> 00:46:47,932
- None of us killed anybody.
- Then that's all, I guess.

630
00:46:52,143 --> 00:46:54,668
- <i>Bring 'em along.</i>
- <i>You don't mean you're</i>
<i>gonna do it, really?</i>

631
00:46:54,745 --> 00:46:56,906
- Pull!
- You got to wait, I tell you!

632
00:46:56,981 --> 00:47:00,178
- You got to give us some time!
- [ Men Chattering ]

633
00:47:00,251 --> 00:47:03,015
You've got to give us some time!
You got to listen to us!

634
00:47:03,087 --> 00:47:06,318
- We haven't done anything.
- Throw the other rope up.

635
00:47:06,390 --> 00:47:09,223
Remember,
the Mexican's mine.

636
00:47:11,395 --> 00:47:14,023
My kids--
One of'em is just a baby.

637
00:47:14,098 --> 00:47:16,862
Just a little baby,
and they haven't got a thing
to go on! Nothing!

638
00:47:16,934 --> 00:47:20,995
I've got to write a letter!
If you're human, you'll give me
time to write a letter!

639
00:47:21,072 --> 00:47:24,371
- That ain't askin' much.
- They're scared and trying
to put it off, that's all.

640
00:47:24,442 --> 00:47:27,240
Yeah. You want Tyler
and the sheriff to get here
and the job not done?

641
00:47:27,311 --> 00:47:31,805
- They won't come in time.
- I believe you're right, Mr. Davies.

642
00:47:31,882 --> 00:47:34,646
Though I doubt
if you want to be.

643
00:47:34,718 --> 00:47:37,050
What time is it?

644
00:47:38,055 --> 00:47:40,489
Five minutes after 3:00.

645
00:47:40,558 --> 00:47:45,120
All right. We don't want to give
anyone cause for complaint.

646
00:47:45,196 --> 00:47:49,098
<i>With your permission, gentlemen,</i>
<i>we'll wait... till daylight.</i>

647
00:47:49,166 --> 00:47:52,329
Bring 'em back.
That'll give you time, Reverend...

648
00:47:52,403 --> 00:47:55,463
to finish your business at leisure.

649
00:47:55,539 --> 00:47:59,305
Sure. And them time
to think it over.

650
00:48:01,078 --> 00:48:04,138
- I can't write like this.
- Very well, untie them.

651
00:48:04,215 --> 00:48:08,811
